      {
        "id": 3855428,
        "name": "Chris Kissack",
        "username": "Chris_Kissack",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/chris_kissack/{size}/270050_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-07-26T09:44:48.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>It\u2019s a nice wine, an indicator of the increasing importance of dry wines in helping Sauternes estates to balance the books. There is a move towards making dry whites not as \u201calso rans\u201d, but as \u201cgrands vins\u201d of equal significance to the sweet wines. Hence the price point for this cuv\u00e9e, I guess. Suduiraut have done exactly the same thing with their refashioned portfolio of dry white wines, also released for the first time in the 2020 vintage.</p>\n<p>I like the 2020 Guiraud Grand Vin Blanc Sec, although perhaps not as much as some did. The 2020 vintage didn\u2019t exactly imbue the whites of Bordeaux with thrilling acidities (I was surprised to learn that they put a portion of the blend through malolactic as well). I look forward to tasting the 2021 blend, given that the 2021 whites have my kind of acidity! But the 2020 does have plenty of appealing fruit concentration and texture. There is a full review and more background info (perhaps not that much more than you already have in the mailer you posted above though) on my site. It\u2019s a free-to-read page, but as it is a commercial site with a paywall I don\u2019t think I can post a link for you.</p>",
